# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: zk-snarks
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A **blockchain** is a distributed ledger with growing lists of records (*blocks*) that are securely linked together via cryptographic hashes.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Each block contains a cryptographic hash of the previous block, a timestamp, and transaction data (generally represented as a Merkle tree, where data nodes are represented by leaves).
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Since each block contains information about the previous block, they effectively form a *chain* (*viz.* linked list data structure), with each additional block linking to the ones before it.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Consequently, blockchain transactions are resistant to alteration because, once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be changed retroactively without altering all subsequent blocks and obtaining network consensus to accept these changes.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Blockchains are typically managed by a peer-to-peer (P2P) computer network for use as a public distributed ledger, where nodes collectively adhere to a consensus algorithm protocol to add and validate new transaction blocks.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Although blockchain records are not unalterable, since blockchain forks are possible, blockchains may be considered secure by design and exemplify a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A blockchain was created by a person (or group of people) using the name (or pseudonym) Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008 to serve as the public distributed ledger for bitcoin cryptocurrency transactions, based on previous work by Stuart Haber, W.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The implementation of the blockchain within bitcoin made it the first digital currency to solve the double-spending problem without the need for a trusted authority or central server.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The bitcoin design has inspired other applications and blockchains that are readable by the public and are widely used by cryptocurrencies.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The blockchain may be considered a type of payment rail.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Private blockchains have been proposed for business use.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] *Computerworld* called the marketing of such privatized blockchains without a proper security model "snake oil"; however, others have argued that permissioned blockchains, if carefully designed, may be more decentralized and therefore more secure in practice than permissionless ones.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Cryptographer David Chaum first proposed a blockchain-like protocol in his 1982 dissertation "Computer Systems Established, Maintained, and Trusted by Mutually Suspicious Groups".
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Further work on a cryptographically secured chain of blocks was described in 1991 by Stuart Haber and W.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] They wanted to implement a system wherein document timestamps could not be tampered with.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In 1992, Haber, Stornetta, and Dave Bayer incorporated Merkle trees into the design, which improved its efficiency by allowing several document certificates to be collected into one block.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Under their company Surety, their document certificate hashes have been published in *The New York Times* every week since 1995.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The first decentralized blockchain was conceptualized by a person (or group of people) known as Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Nakamoto improved the design in an important way using a Hashcash-like method to timestamp blocks without requiring them to be signed by a trusted party and introducing a difficulty parameter to stabilize the rate at which blocks are added to the chain.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The design was implemented the following year by Nakamoto as a core component of the cryptocurrency bitcoin, where it serves as the public ledger for all transactions on the network.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In August 2014, the bitcoin blockchain file size, containing records of all transactions that have occurred on the network, reached 20 GB (gigabytes).
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] By 2024, the bitcoin blockchain exceeded 600 GB.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The words *block* and *chain* were used separately in Satoshi Nakamoto's original paper, but were eventually popularized as a single word, *blockchain*, by 2016.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] According to Accenture, an application of the diffusion of innovations theory suggests that blockchains attained a 13.5% adoption rate within financial services in 2016, therefore reaching the early adopters' phase.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Industry trade groups joined to create the Global Blockchain Forum in 2016, an initiative of the Chamber of Digital Commerce.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In May 2018, Gartner found that only 1% of CIOs indicated any kind of blockchain adoption within their organisations, and only 8% of CIOs were in the short-term "planning or [looking at] active experimentation with blockchain".
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] For the year 2019 Gartner reported 5% of CIOs believed blockchain technology was a 'game-changer' for their business.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A blockchain is a decentralized, distributed, and often public, digital ledger consisting of records called *blocks* that are used to record transactions across many computers so that any involved block cannot be altered retroactively, without the alteration of all subsequent blocks.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] This allows the participants to verify and audit transactions independently and relatively inexpensively.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A blockchain database is managed autonomously using a peer-to-peer network and a distributed timestamping server.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] They are authenticated by mass collaboration powered by collective self-interests.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Such a design facilitates robust workflow where participants' uncertainty regarding data security is marginal.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The use of a blockchain removes the characteristic of infinite reproducibility from a digital asset.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] It confirms that each unit of value was transferred only once, solving the long-standing problem of double-spending.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A blockchain has been described as a *value-exchange protocol*.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Blocks hold batches of valid transactions that are hashed and encoded into a Merkle tree.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Each block includes the cryptographic hash of the prior block in the blockchain, linking the two.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] This iterative process confirms the integrity of the previous block, all the way back to the initial block, which is known as the *genesis block* (Block 0).
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] To assure the integrity of a block and the data contained in it, the block is usually digitally signed.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Sometimes separate blocks can be produced concurrently, creating a temporary fork.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In addition to a secure hash-based history, any blockchain has a specified algorithm for scoring different versions of the history so that one with a higher score can be selected over others.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Blocks not selected for inclusion in the chain are called orphan blocks.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Peers supporting the database have different versions of the history from time to time.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] They keep only the highest-scoring version of the database known to them.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Whenever a peer receives a higher-scoring version (usually the old version with a single new block added) they extend or overwrite their own database and retransmit the improvement to their peers.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] There is never an absolute guarantee that any particular entry will remain in the best version of history forever.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Blockchains are typically built to add the score of new blocks onto old blocks and are given incentives to extend with new blocks rather than overwrite old blocks.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Therefore, the probability of an entry becoming superseded decreases exponentially as more blocks are built on top of it, eventually becoming very low.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] For example, bitcoin uses a proof-of-work system, where the chain with the most cumulative proof-of-work is considered the valid one by the network.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] There are a number of methods that can be used to demonstrate a sufficient level of computation.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Within a blockchain the computation is carried out redundantly rather than in the traditional segregated and parallel manner.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The *block time* is the average time it takes for the network to generate one extra block in the blockchain.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] By the time of block completion, the included data becomes verifiable.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In cryptocurrency, this is practically when the transaction takes place, so a shorter block time means faster transactions.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Since 2022, the block time for Ethereum is set to exactly 12 seconds, while for bitcoin it is on average 10 minutes.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A *hard fork* is a change to the blockchain protocol that is not backward compatible and requires all users to upgrade their software in order to continue participating in the network.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In a hard fork, the network splits into two separate versions: one that follows the new rules and one that follows the old rules.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] For example, Ethereum was hard forked in 2016 to "make whole" the investors in The DAO, which had been hacked by exploiting a vulnerability in its code.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In this case, the fork resulted in a split creating Ethereum and Ethereum Classic chains.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In 2014, the Nxt community was asked to consider a hard fork that would have led to a rollback of the blockchain records to mitigate the effects of a theft of 50 million NXT from a major cryptocurrency exchange.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The hard fork proposal was rejected, and some of the funds were recovered after negotiations and ransom payment.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Alternatively, to prevent a permanent split, a majority of nodes using the new software may return to the old rules, as was the case with Bitcoin split on 12 March 2013.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A more recent hard-fork example is of Bitcoin in 2017, which resulted in a split creating Bitcoin Cash.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The network split was mainly due to a disagreement in how to increase the transactions per second to accommodate for demand.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] By storing data across its peer-to-peer network, the blockchain eliminates some risks that come with data being held centrally.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The decentralized blockchain may use ad hoc message passing and distributed networking.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In a so-called "51% attack" a central entity gains control of more than half of a network and can then manipulate that specific blockchain record at will, allowing double-spending.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Blockchain security methods include the use of public-key cryptography.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A *public key* (a long, random-looking string of numbers) is an address on the blockchain.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Value tokens sent across the network are recorded as belonging to that address.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A *private key* is like a password that gives its owner access to their digital assets or the means to otherwise interact with the various capabilities that blockchains now support.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Data stored on the blockchain is generally considered incorruptible.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Every node in a decentralized system has a copy of the blockchain.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Data quality is maintained by massive database replication and computational trust.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] No centralized "official" copy exists and no user is "trusted" more than any other.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Transactions are broadcast to the network using the software.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Messages are delivered on a best-effort basis.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Early blockchains rely on energy-intensive mining nodes to validate transactions, add them to the block they are building, and then broadcast the completed block to other nodes.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Blockchains use various time-stamping schemes, such as proof-of-work, to serialize changes.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Later consensus methods include proof of stake.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The growth of a decentralized blockchain is accompanied by the risk of centralization because the computer resources required to process larger amounts of data become more expensive.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Finality is the level of confidence that the well-formed block recently appended to the blockchain will not be revoked in the future (is "finalized") and thus can be trusted.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Byzantine fault tolerance-based proof-of-stake protocols purport to provide so called "absolute finality": a randomly chosen validator proposes a block, the rest of validators vote on it, and, if a supermajority decision approves it, the block is irreversibly committed into the blockchain.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A modification of this method, an "economic finality", is used in practical protocols, like the Casper protocol used in Ethereum: validators which sign two different blocks at the same position in the blockchain are subject to "slashing", where their leveraged stake is forfeited.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Open blockchains are more user-friendly than some traditional ownership records, which, while open to the public, still require physical access to view.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Because all early blockchains were permissionless, controversy has arisen over the blockchain definition.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] An issue in this ongoing debate is whether a private system with verifiers tasked and authorized (permissioned) by a central authority should be considered a blockchain.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Proponents of permissioned or private chains argue that the term "blockchain" may be applied to any **data structure** that batches data into time-stamped blocks.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] These blockchains serve as a distributed version of multiversion concurrency control (MVCC) in databases.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Just as MVCC prevents two transactions from concurrently modifying a single object in a database, blockchains prevent two transactions from spending the same single output in a blockchain.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Opponents say that permissioned systems resemble traditional corporate databases, not supporting decentralized data verification, and that such systems are not hardened against operator tampering and revision.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] An advantage to an open, permissionless, or public, blockchain network is that guarding against bad actors is not required and no access control is needed.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] This means that applications can be added to the network without the approval or trust of others, using the blockchain as a transport layer.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies currently secure their blockchain by requiring new entries to include proof of work.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] To prolong the blockchain, bitcoin uses Hashcash puzzles.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] While Hashcash was designed in 1997 by Adam Back, the original idea was first proposed by Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor and Eli Ponyatovski in their 1992 paper "Pricing via Processing or Combatting Junk Mail".
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In 2016, venture capital investment for blockchain-related projects was weakening in the US but increasing in China.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Bitcoin and many other cryptocurrencies use open (public) blockchains.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] As of April 2018, bitcoin has the highest market capitalization.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Permissioned blockchains use an access control layer to govern who has access to the network.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] It has been argued that permissioned blockchains can guarantee a certain level of decentralization, if carefully designed, as opposed to permissionless blockchains, which are often centralized in practice.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Nikolai Hampton argued in *Computerworld* that "There is also no need for a '51 percent' attack on a private blockchain, as the private blockchain (most likely) already controls 100 percent of all block creation resources.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] It's unlikely that any private blockchain will try to protect records using gigawatts of computing power — it's time-consuming and expensive." He also said, "Within a private blockchain there is also no 'race'; there's no incentive to use more power or discover blocks faster than competitors.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The analysis of public blockchains has become increasingly important with the popularity of bitcoin, Ethereum, litecoin and other cryptocurrencies.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A blockchain, if it is public, provides access to anyone to observe and analyse the chain data, given the know-how.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The process of understanding and accessing the flow of crypto has been an issue for many cryptocurrencies, crypto exchanges and banks.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The reason for this is accusations of blockchain-enabled cryptocurrencies enabling illicit dark market trading of drugs, weapons, money laundering, etc.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A common belief has been that cryptocurrency is private and untraceable, thus leading many actors to use it for illegal purposes.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] This is changing now that specialised tech companies provide blockchain tracking services, making crypto exchanges, law-enforcement and banks more aware of what is happening with crypto funds and fiat-crypto exchanges.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The development, some argue, has led criminals to prioritise the use of new cryptos such as Monero.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In April 2016, Standards Australia submitted a proposal to the International Organization for Standardization to consider developing standards to support blockchain technology.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] This proposal resulted in the creation of ISO Technical Committee 307, Blockchain and Distributed Ledger Technologies.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The technical committee has working groups relating to blockchain terminology, reference architecture, security and privacy, identity, smart contracts, governance and interoperability for blockchain and DLT, as well as standards specific to industry sectors and generic government requirements.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Many other national standards bodies and open standards bodies are also working on blockchain standards.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Although most of blockchain implementation are decentralized and distributed, Oracle launched a centralized blockchain table feature in Oracle 21c database.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The Blockchain Table in Oracle 21c database is a centralized blockchain which provide immutable feature.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Compared to decentralized blockchains, centralized blockchains normally can provide a higher throughput and lower latency of transactions than consensus-based distributed blockchains.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Currently, there are at least four types of blockchain networks — public blockchains, private blockchains, consortium blockchains and hybrid blockchains.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A public blockchain has no access restrictions.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Anyone with an Internet connection can send transactions to it as well as become a validator (i.e., participate in the execution of a consensus protocol).
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Usually, such networks offer economic incentives for those who secure them and utilize some type of a proof-of-stake or proof-of-work algorithm.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Some of the largest, most known public blockchains are the bitcoin blockchain and the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] One cannot join it unless invited by the network administrators.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Participant and validator access is restricted.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] To distinguish between open blockchains and other peer-to-peer decentralized database applications that are not open ad-hoc compute clusters, the terminology Distributed Ledger (DLT) is normally used for private blockchains.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A hybrid blockchain has a combination of centralized and decentralized features.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The exact workings of the chain can vary based on which portions of centralization and decentralization are used.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A sidechain is a designation for a blockchain ledger that runs in parallel to a primary blockchain.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A consortium blockchain is a type of blockchain that combines elements of both public and private blockchains.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In a consortium blockchain, a group of organizations come together to create and operate the blockchain, rather than a single entity.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The consortium members jointly manage the blockchain network and are responsible for validating transactions.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are permissioned, meaning that only certain individuals or organizations are allowed to participate in the network.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] This allows for greater control over who can access the blockchain and helps to ensure that sensitive information is kept confidential.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are commonly used in industries where multiple organizations need to collaborate on a common goal, such as supply chain management or financial services.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] One advantage of consortium blockchains is that they can be more efficient and scalable than public blockchains, as the number of nodes required to validate transactions is typically smaller.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Additionally, consortium blockchains can provide greater security and reliability than private blockchains, as the consortium members work together to maintain the network.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Some examples of consortium blockchains include Quorum and Hyperledger.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The primary use of blockchains is as a distributed ledger for cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin; there were also a few other operational products that had matured from proof of concept by late 2016.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] As of 2016, some businesses have been testing the technology and conducting low-level implementation to gauge blockchain's effects on organizational efficiency in their back office.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In 2019, it was estimated that around $2.9 billion were invested in blockchain technology, which represents an 89% increase from the year prior.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A report from to PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) in 2021 said that blockchain technology had the potential to generate an annual business value of more than $3 trillion by 2030.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] PwC surveyed 600 business executives and determined that 84% have at least some exposure to utilizing blockchain technology.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In 2019, the BBC World Service radio and podcast series *50 Things That Made the Modern Economy* identified blockchain as a technology that would have far-reaching consequences for economics and society.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The economist and *Financial Times* journalist and broadcaster Tim Harford discussed why the underlying technology might have much wider applications and the challenges that needed to be overcome.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] His first broadcast was on 29 June 2019.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Most cryptocurrencies are designed to gradually decrease the production of that currency, placing a cap on the total amount of that currency that will ever be in circulation.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Compared with ordinary currencies held by financial institutions or kept as cash on hand, cryptocurrencies can be more difficult for seizure by law enforcement.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The validity of each cryptocurrency's coins is provided by a blockchain.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A blockchain is a continuously growing list of records, called blocks, which are linked and secured using cryptography.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Each block typically contains a hash pointer as a link to a previous block, a timestamp and transaction data.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] By design, blockchains are inherently resistant to modification of the data.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] It is "an open, distributed ledger that can record transactions between two parties efficiently and in a verifiable and permanent way".
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] For use as a distributed ledger, a blockchain is typically managed by a peer-to-peer network collectively adhering to a protocol for validating new blocks.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be altered retroactively without the alteration of all subsequent blocks, which requires collusion of the network majority.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Blockchains are secure by design and are an example of a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Decentralized consensus has therefore been achieved with a blockchain.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In the context of cryptocurrencies, the blockchain serves as a public ledger for all transactions.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Cryptocurrencies use various timestamping schemes to "prove the validity of transactions added to the blockchain ledger without the need for a trusted third party".
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The first cryptocurrency was Bitcoin, which was first released as open-source software in 2009.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] As cryptocurrencies have gained prominence, several countries have made advancements in their private and commercial law treatment to address legal uncertainties.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In the United States, for example, the 2022 amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced Article 12, which establishes "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] This framework provides legal clarity for the ownership, transfer, and use of cryptocurrencies as CERs, with the concept of "control" serving as a functional equivalent to possession for digital assets.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] These reforms aim to align legal standards with market practices, reducing title disputes and supporting the integration of cryptocurrencies into commercial transactions.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Blockchain-based smart contracts are contracts that can be partially or fully executed or enforced without human interaction.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] One of the main objectives of a smart contract is automated escrow.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A key feature of smart contracts is that they do not need a trusted third party (such as a trustee) to act as an intermediary between contracting entities — the blockchain network executes the contract on its own.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] This may reduce friction between entities when transferring value and could subsequently open the door to a higher level of transaction automation.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] An IMF staff discussion from 2018 reported that smart contracts based on blockchain technology might reduce moral hazards and optimize the use of contracts in general, but "no viable smart contract systems have yet emerged." Due to the lack of widespread use, their legal status was unclear.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] According to *Reason* in 2016, many banks have expressed interest in implementing distributed ledgers for use in banking and are cooperating with companies creating private blockchains.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] According to a September 2016 IBM study, this implementation was occurring faster than expected.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Blockchain technology has been proposed as a way to speed up back office settlement systems.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In 2017, UBS opened a lab dedicated to researching how blockchain technology could be used in financial services.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In 2017, the German bank Berenberg described blockchain as an "overhyped technology" that has had a large number of "proofs of concept", but still has major challenges, and very few success stories.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Blockchain technology has allowed for new forms of fundraising such as initial coin offerings (ICOs) and security token offerings (STOs), also sometimes referred to as digital security offerings (DSOs).
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] STO/DSOs may be conducted privately or on public, regulated stock exchange and are used to tokenize assets such as company shares, intellectual property, real estate, and others.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Blockchain technology, such as cryptocurrencies and non-fungible tokens (NFTs), has been used in video games for monetization.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Many live-service games offer in-game customization options, such as character skins or other in-game items, which the players can earn and trade with other players using in-game currency.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Blockchain games typically allow players to trade these in-game items for cryptocurrency, which can then be exchanged for money.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The first known game to use blockchain technologies was *CryptoKitties*, launched in November 2017, where the player would purchase NFTs with Ethereum cryptocurrency, each NFT consisting of a virtual pet that the player could breed with others to create offspring with combined traits as new NFTs.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The game made headlines in December 2017 when one virtual pet sold for more than US$100,000.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] *CryptoKitties* also illustrated scalability problems for games on Ethereum when it created significant congestion on the Ethereum network in early 2018 with approximately 30% of all Ethereum transactions being for the game.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] By the early 2020s, there had not been a breakout success in video games using blockchain, as these games tend to focus on using blockchain for speculation instead of more traditional forms of gameplay, which offers limited appeal to most players.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Such games also represent a high risk to investors as their revenues can be difficult to predict.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Several major publishers, including Ubisoft, Electronic Arts, and Take Two Interactive, have stated that blockchain and NFT-based games are under serious consideration for their companies in the future.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Valve's prior history with gambling, specifically skin gambling, was speculated to be a factor in the decision to ban blockchain games.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] There have been several different efforts to employ blockchains in supply chain management.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] There are several different efforts to offer domain name services via the blockchain.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] These domain names can be controlled by the use of a private key, which purports to allow for uncensorable websites.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] This would also bypass a registrar's ability to suppress domains used for fraud, abuse, or illegal content.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Namecoin is a cryptocurrency that supports the ".bit" top-level domain (TLD).
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Namecoin was forked from bitcoin in 2011.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The .bit TLD is not sanctioned by ICANN, instead requiring an alternative DNS root.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] As of 2015, .bit was used by 28 websites, out of 120,000 registered names.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Namecoin was dropped by OpenNIC in 2019, due to malware and potential other legal issues.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Other blockchain alternatives to ICANN include *The Handshake Network*, *EmerDNS*, and *Unstoppable Domains*.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Specific TLDs include ".eth", ".luxe", and ".kred", which are associated with the Ethereum blockchain through the Ethereum Name Service (ENS).
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The .kred TLD also acts as an alternative to conventional cryptocurrency wallet addresses as a convenience for transferring cryptocurrency.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Blockchain technology can be used to create a permanent, public, transparent ledger system for compiling data on sales, tracking digital use and payments to content creators, such as wireless users or musicians.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The Gartner 2019 CIO Survey reported 2% of higher education respondents had launched blockchain projects and another 18% were planning academic projects in the next 24 months.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In 2017, IBM partnered with ASCAP and PRS for Music to adopt blockchain technology in music distribution.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] New distribution methods are available for the insurance industry such as peer-to-peer insurance, parametric insurance and microinsurance following the adoption of blockchain.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The sharing economy and IoT are also set to benefit from blockchains because they involve many collaborating peers.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The use of blockchain in libraries is being studied with a grant from the U.S.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Institute of Museum and Library Services.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Other blockchain designs include Hyperledger, a collaborative effort from the Linux Foundation to support blockchain-based distributed ledgers, with projects under this initiative including Hyperledger Burrow (by Monax) and Hyperledger Fabric (spearheaded by IBM).
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Another is Quorum, a permissioned private blockchain by JPMorgan Chase with private storage, used for contract applications.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Oracle introduced a blockchain table feature in its Oracle 21c database.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Blockchain is also being used in peer-to-peer energy trading.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Blockchain could be used in detecting counterfeits by associating unique identifiers to products, documents and shipments, and storing records associated with transactions that cannot be forged or altered.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] It is however argued that blockchain technology needs to be supplemented with technologies that provide a strong binding between physical objects and blockchain systems, as well as provisions for content creator verification *ala* KYC standards.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The EUIPO established an Anti-Counterfeiting Blockathon Forum, with the objective of "defining, piloting and implementing" an anti-counterfeiting infrastructure at the European level.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The Dutch Standardisation organisation NEN uses blockchain together with QR Codes to authenticate certificates.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Beijing and Shanghai are among the cities designated by China to trial blockchain applications as January 30, 2022.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In Chinese legal proceedings, blockchain technology was first accepted as a method for authenticating internet evidence by the Hangzhou Internet Court in 2019 and has since been accepted by other Chinese courts.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] With the increasing number of blockchain systems appearing, even only those that support cryptocurrencies, blockchain interoperability is becoming a topic of major importance.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The objective is to support transferring assets from one blockchain system to another blockchain system.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Wegner stated that "interoperability is the ability of two or more software components to cooperate despite differences in language, interface, and execution platform".
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The objective of blockchain interoperability is therefore to support such cooperation among blockchain systems, despite those kinds of differences.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] There are already several blockchain interoperability solutions available.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] They can be classified into three categories: cryptocurrency interoperability approaches, blockchain engines, and blockchain connectors.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Several individual IETF participants produced the draft of a blockchain interoperability architecture.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Some cryptocurrencies use blockchain mining, namely the peer-to-peer computer computations by which transactions are validated and verified.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In June 2018, the Bank for International Settlements criticized the use of public proof-of-work blockchains for their high energy consumption.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Early concern over the high energy consumption was a factor in later blockchains such as Cardano (2017), Solana (2020) and Polkadot (2020) adopting the less energy-intensive proof-of-stake model.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Researchers have estimated that bitcoin consumes 100,000 times as much energy as proof-of-stake networks.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In 2021, a study by Cambridge University determined that bitcoin (at 121 terawatt-hours per year) used more electricity than Argentina (at 121TWh) and the Netherlands (109TWh).
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] According to Digiconomist, one bitcoin transaction required 708 kilowatt-hours of electrical energy, the amount an average U.S. household consumed in 24 days.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Treasury secretary Janet Yellen called bitcoin "an extremely inefficient way to conduct transactions", saying "the amount of energy consumed in processing those transactions is staggering".
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Nicholas Weaver, of the International Computer Science Institute at the University of California, Berkeley, examined blockchain's online security, and the energy efficiency of proof-of-work public blockchains, and in both cases found it grossly inadequate.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The 31TWh-45TWh of electricity used for bitcoin in 2018 produced 17–23 million tonnes of CO2.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] By 2022, the University of Cambridge and Digiconomist estimated that the two largest proof-of-work blockchains, bitcoin and Ethereum, together used twice as much electricity in one year as the whole of Sweden, leading to the release of up to 120 million tonnes of CO2 each year.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Some cryptocurrency developers are considering moving from the proof-of-work model to the proof-of-stake model.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In Sept, 2022, Ethereum converted from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In October 2014, the MIT Bitcoin Club, with funding from MIT alumni, provided undergraduate students at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology access to $100 of bitcoin.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The adoption rates, as studied by Catalini and Tucker (2016), revealed that when people who typically adopt technologies early are given delayed access, they tend to reject the technology.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Many universities have founded departments focusing on crypto and blockchain, including MIT, in 2017.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In the same year, Edinburgh became "one of the first big European universities to launch a blockchain course", according to the *Financial Times*.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Motivations for adopting blockchain technology (an aspect of innovation adoption) have been investigated by researchers.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] For example, Janssen, et al. provided a framework for analysis, and Koens & Poll pointed out that adoption could be heavily driven by non-technical factors.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Based on behavioral models, Li has discussed the differences between adoption at the individual level and organizational levels.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Scholars in business and management have started studying the role of blockchains to support collaboration.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] It has been argued that blockchains can foster both cooperation (i.e., prevention of opportunistic behavior) and coordination (i.e., communication and information sharing).
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Thanks to reliability, transparency, traceability of records, and information immutability, blockchains facilitate collaboration in a way that differs both from the traditional use of contracts and from relational norms.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Contrary to contracts, blockchains do not directly rely on the legal system to enforce agreements.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In addition, contrary to the use of relational norms, blockchains do not require a trust or direct connections between collaborators.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The need for internal audits to provide effective oversight of organizational efficiency will require a change in the way that information is accessed in new formats.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Blockchain adoption requires a framework to identify the risk of exposure associated with transactions using blockchain.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The Institute of Internal Auditors has identified the need for internal auditors to address this transformational technology.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] New methods are required to develop audit plans that identify threats and risks.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The Internal Audit Foundation study, *Blockchain and Internal Audit,* assesses these factors.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has outlined new roles for auditors as a result of blockchain.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In blockchain technology, a **testnet** is an instance of a blockchain powered by the same or a newer version of the underlying software, to be used for testing and experimentation without risk to real funds or the main chain.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Testnet coins are separate and distinct from the official *mainnet* coins, don't have value, and can be obtained freely from *faucets*.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Testnets allow for the development of blockchain applications without the risk of losing funds.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Using testnets, a bug was discovered in the Bitcoin Core software that gave miners the ability to take down essential parts of the Bitcoin infrastructure (nodes) by sending a 'bad' block to the blockchain.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A **mainnet** (short for *main network*) is the fully operational version of a blockchain where real transactions occur, as opposed to a testnet.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] It is secured through consensus mechanisms like Proof of Work or Proof of Stake and supports smart contracts, token transfers, and decentralized applications.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] A *mainnet launch* marks the transition from a testnet to a live blockchain, involving security audits, network deployment, and token migration.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] In September 2015, the first peer-reviewed academic journal dedicated to cryptocurrency and blockchain technology research, *Ledger*, was announced.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The inaugural issue was published in December 2016.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The journal covers aspects of mathematics, computer science, engineering, law, economics and philosophy that relate to cryptocurrencies.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] The journal encourages authors to digitally sign a file hash of submitted papers, which are then timestamped into the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:zk-snarks/blockchain] Authors are also asked to include a personal bitcoin address on the first page of their papers for non-repudiation purposes.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashing is a one-directional mathematical operation which is quick to calculate, yet hard to reverse.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] So password storage and digital signatures benefit from hashes.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Even a small change in the input results in a very different hash.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] So it is useful to check if two copies of data or software match.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Typically the operation works on a block of input data; the hash output is then hashed with the next block, creating a new hash reflecting everything to that point; again and again until the final hash reflects everything through the final block.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Cryptographic hash functions have many information-security applications, notably in digital signatures, message authentication codes (MACs), and other forms of authentication.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] They can also be used as ordinary hash functions, to index data in hash tables, for fingerprinting, to detect duplicate data or uniquely identify files, and as checksums to detect accidental data corruption.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Indeed, in information-security contexts, cryptographic hash values are sometimes called (*digital*) *fingerprints*, *checksums*, (*message*) *digests*, or just *hash values*, even though all these terms stand for more general functions with rather different properties and purposes.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic hash functions are used in hash tables and to detect accidental errors; their constructions frequently provide no resistance to a deliberate attack.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a denial-of-service attack on hash tables is possible if the collisions are easy to find, as in the case of linear cyclic redundancy check (CRC) functions.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Most cryptographic hash functions are designed to take a string of any length as input and produce a fixed-length hash value.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] A cryptographic hash function must be able to withstand all known types of cryptanalytic attack.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance implies second pre-image resistance but does not imply pre-image resistance.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The weaker assumption is always preferred in theoretical cryptography, but in practice, a hash-function that is only second pre-image resistant is considered insecure and is therefore not recommended for real applications.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Informally, these properties mean that a malicious adversary cannot replace or modify the input data without changing its digest.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Thus, if two strings have the same digest, one can be very confident that they are identical.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Second pre-image resistance prevents an attacker from crafting a document with the same hash as a document the attacker cannot control.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance prevents an attacker from creating two distinct documents with the same hash.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] A function meeting these criteria may still have undesirable properties.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Currently, popular cryptographic hash functions are vulnerable to *length-extension* attacks: given hash(*m*) and len(*m*) but not *m*, by choosing a suitable *m*′ an attacker can calculate hash(*m* ∥ *m*′), where ∥ denotes concatenation.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] This property can be used to break naive authentication schemes based on hash functions.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The HMAC construction works around these problems.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] In practice, collision resistance is insufficient for many practical uses.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] In addition to collision resistance, it should be impossible for an adversary to find two messages with substantially similar digests; or to infer any useful information about the data, given only its digest.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, a hash function should behave as much as possible like a random function (often called a random oracle in proofs of security) while still being deterministic and efficiently computable.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] This rules out functions like the SWIFFT function, which can be rigorously proven to be collision-resistant assuming that certain problems on ideal lattices are computationally difficult, but, as a linear function, does not satisfy these additional properties.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Checksum algorithms, such as CRC-32 and other cyclic redundancy checks, are designed to meet much weaker requirements and are generally unsuitable as cryptographic hash functions.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a CRC was used for message integrity in the WEP encryption standard, but an attack was readily discovered, which exploited the linearity of the checksum.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] In cryptographic practice, "difficult" generally means "almost certainly beyond the reach of any adversary who must be prevented from breaking the system for as long as the security of the system is deemed important".
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The meaning of the term is therefore somewhat dependent on the application since the effort that a malicious agent may put into the task is usually proportional to their expected gain.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] However, since the needed effort usually multiplies with the digest length, even a thousand-fold advantage in processing power can be neutralized by adding a dozen bits to the latter.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] For messages selected from a limited set of messages, for example passwords or other short messages, it can be feasible to invert a hash by trying all possible messages in the set.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Because cryptographic hash functions are typically designed to be computed quickly, special key derivation functions that require greater computing resources have been developed that make such brute-force attacks more difficult.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] In some theoretical analyses "difficult" has a specific mathematical meaning, such as "not solvable in asymptotic polynomial time".
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Such interpretations of *difficulty* are important in the study of provably secure cryptographic hash functions but do not usually have a strong connection to practical security.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, an exponential-time algorithm can sometimes still be fast enough to make a feasible attack.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Conversely, a polynomial-time algorithm (e.g., one that requires *n*20 steps for *n*-digit keys) may be too slow for any practical use.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] An illustration of the potential use of a cryptographic hash is as follows: Alice poses a tough math problem to Bob and claims that she has solved it.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Bob would like to try it himself, but would yet like to be sure that Alice is not bluffing.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Therefore, Alice writes down her solution, computes its hash, and tells Bob the hash value (whilst keeping the solution secret).
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Then, when Bob comes up with the solution himself a few days later, Alice can prove that she had the solution earlier by revealing it and having Bob hash it and then check that it matches the hash value given to him before.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] An important application of secure hashes is the verification of message integrity.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Comparing message digests (hash digests over the message) calculated before, and after, transmission can determine whether any changes have been made to the message or file.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5, SHA-1, or SHA-2 hash digests are sometimes published on websites or forums to allow verification of integrity for downloaded files, including files retrieved using file sharing such as mirroring.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] This practice establishes a chain of trust as long as the hashes are posted on a trusted site – usually the originating site – authenticated by HTTPS.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Using a cryptographic hash and a chain of trust detects malicious changes to the file.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic error-detecting codes such as cyclic redundancy checks only prevent against *non-malicious* alterations of the file, since an intentional spoof can readily be crafted to have the colliding code value.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Almost all digital signature schemes require a cryptographic hash to be calculated over the message.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] This allows the signature calculation to be performed on the relatively small, statically sized hash digest.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The message is considered authentic if the signature verification succeeds given the signature and recalculated hash digest over the message.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] So the message integrity property of the cryptographic hash is used to create secure and efficient digital signature schemes.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Password verification commonly relies on cryptographic hashes.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Storing all user passwords as cleartext can result in a massive security breach if the password file is compromised.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] One way to reduce this danger is to only store the hash digest of each password.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] To authenticate a user, the password presented by the user is hashed and compared with the stored hash.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] A password reset method is required when password hashing is performed; original passwords cannot be recalculated from the stored hash value.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] However, use of standard cryptographic hash functions, such as the SHA series, is no longer considered safe for password storage.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] These algorithms are designed to be computed quickly, so if the hashed values are compromised, it is possible to try guessed passwords at high rates.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Common graphics processing units can try billions of possible passwords each second.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Password hash functions that perform key stretching – such as PBKDF2, scrypt or Argon2 – commonly use repeated invocations of a cryptographic hash to increase the time (and in some cases computer memory) required to perform brute-force attacks on stored password hash digests.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] For details, see § Attacks on hashed passwords.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] A password hash also requires the use of a large random, non-secret salt value that can be stored with the password hash.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The salt is hashed with the password, altering the password hash mapping for each password, thereby making it infeasible for an adversary to store tables of precomputed hash values to which the password hash digest can be compared or to test a large number of purloined hash values in parallel.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] A proof-of-work system (or protocol, or function) is an economic measure to deter denial-of-service attacks and other service abuses such as spam on a network by requiring some work from the service requester, usually meaning processing time by a computer.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] A key feature of these schemes is their asymmetry: the work must be moderately hard (but feasible) on the requester side but easy to check for the service provider.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] One popular system – used in Bitcoin mining and Hashcash – uses partial hash inversions to prove that work was done, to unlock a mining reward in Bitcoin, and as a good-will token to send an e-mail in Hashcash.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender is required to find a message whose hash value begins with a number of zero bits.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The average work that the sender needs to perform in order to find a valid message is exponential in the number of zero bits required in the hash value, while the recipient can verify the validity of the message by executing a single hash function.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in Hashcash, a sender is asked to generate a header whose 160-bit SHA-1 hash value has the first 20 bits as zeros.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender will, on average, have to try 219 times to find a valid header.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] A message digest can also serve as a means of reliably identifying a file; several source code management systems, including Git, Mercurial and Monotone, use the sha1sum of various types of content (file content, directory trees, ancestry information, etc.) to uniquely identify them.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashes are used to identify files on peer-to-peer filesharing networks.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, in an ed2k link, an MD4-variant hash is combined with the file size, providing sufficient information for locating file sources, downloading the file, and verifying its contents.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Such file hashes are often the top hash of a hash list or a hash tree, which allows for additional benefits.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] One of the main applications of a hash function is to allow the fast look-up of data in a hash table.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Being hash functions of a particular kind, cryptographic hash functions lend themselves well to this application too.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] However, compared with standard hash functions, cryptographic hash functions tend to be much more expensive computationally.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage (CAS), also referred to as content-addressed storage or fixed-content storage, is a way to store information so it can be retrieved based on its content, not its name or location.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] It has been used for high-speed storage and retrieval of fixed content, such as documents stored for compliance with government regulations.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage is similar to content-addressable memory.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS systems work by passing the content of the file through a cryptographic hash function to generate a unique key, the "content address".
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The file system's directory stores these addresses and a pointer to the physical storage of the content.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Because an attempt to store the same file will generate the same key, CAS systems ensure that the files within them are unique, and because changing the file will result in a new key, CAS systems provide assurance that the file is unchanged.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS became a significant market during the 2000s, especially after the introduction of the 2002 Sarbanes–Oxley Act in the United States which required the storage of enormous numbers of documents for long periods and retrieved only rarely.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Ever-increasing performance of traditional file systems and new software systems have eroded the value of legacy CAS systems, which have become increasingly rare after roughly 2018.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] However, the principles of content addressability continue to be of great interest to computer scientists, and form the core of numerous emerging technologies, such as peer-to-peer file sharing, cryptocurrencies, and distributed computing.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] There are several methods to use a block cipher to build a cryptographic hash function, specifically a one-way compression function.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The methods resemble the block cipher modes of operation usually used for encryption.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Many well-known hash functions, including MD4, MD5, SHA-1 and SHA-2, are built from block-cipher-like components designed for the purpose, with feedback to ensure that the resulting function is not invertible.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 finalists included functions with block-cipher-like components (e.g., Skein, BLAKE) though the function finally selected, Keccak, was built on a cryptographic sponge instead.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] A standard block cipher such as AES can be used in place of these custom block ciphers; that might be useful when an embedded system needs to implement both encryption and hashing with minimal code size or hardware area.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] However, that approach can have costs in efficiency and security.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The ciphers in hash functions are built for hashing: they use large keys and blocks, can efficiently change keys every block, and have been designed and vetted for resistance to related-key attacks.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] General-purpose ciphers tend to have different design goals.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, AES has key and block sizes that make it nontrivial to use to generate long hash values; AES encryption becomes less efficient when the key changes each block; and related-key attacks make it potentially less secure for use in a hash function than for encryption.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function must be able to process an arbitrary-length message into a fixed-length output.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] This can be achieved by breaking the input up into a series of equally sized blocks, and operating on them in sequence using a one-way compression function.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The compression function can either be specially designed for hashing or be built from a block cipher.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function built with the Merkle–Damgård construction is as resistant to collisions as is its compression function; any collision for the full hash function can be traced back to a collision in the compression function.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The last block processed should also be unambiguously length padded; this is crucial to the security of this construction.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] This construction is called the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Most common classical hash functions, including SHA-1 and MD5, take this form.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] A straightforward application of the Merkle–Damgård construction, where the size of hash output is equal to the internal state size (between each compression step), results in a **narrow-pipe** hash design.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] This design causes many inherent flaws, including length-extension, multicollisions, long message attacks, generate-and-paste attacks, and also cannot be parallelized.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] As a result, modern hash functions are built on **wide-pipe** constructions that have a larger internal state size – which range from tweaks of the Merkle–Damgård construction to new constructions such as the sponge construction and HAIFA construction.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] None of the entrants in the NIST hash function competition use a classical Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Meanwhile, truncating the output of a longer hash, such as used in SHA-512/256, also defeats many of these attacks.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Hash functions can be used to build other cryptographic primitives.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] For these other primitives to be cryptographically secure, care must be taken to build them correctly.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Message authentication codes (MACs) (also called keyed hash functions) are often built from hash functions.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Just as block ciphers can be used to build hash functions, hash functions can be used to build block ciphers.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Luby-Rackoff constructions using hash functions can be provably secure if the underlying hash function is secure.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Also, many hash functions (including SHA-1 and SHA-2) are built by using a special-purpose block cipher in a Davies–Meyer or other construction.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] That cipher can also be used in a conventional mode of operation, without the same security guarantees; for example, SHACAL, BEAR and LION.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Pseudorandom number generators (PRNGs) can be built using hash functions.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] This is done by combining a (secret) random seed with a counter and hashing it.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Some hash functions, such as Skein, Keccak, and RadioGatún, output an arbitrarily long stream and can be used as a stream cipher, and stream ciphers can also be built from fixed-length digest hash functions.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Often this is done by first building a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator and then using its stream of random bytes as keystream.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is a stream cipher that uses SHA-1 to generate internal tables, which are then used in a keystream generator more or less unrelated to the hash algorithm.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is not guaranteed to be as strong (or weak) as SHA-1.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Similarly, the key expansion of the HC-128 and HC-256 stream ciphers makes heavy use of the SHA-256 hash function.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Concatenating outputs from multiple hash functions provide collision resistance as good as the strongest of the algorithms included in the concatenated result.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, older versions of Transport Layer Security (TLS) and Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) used concatenated MD5 and SHA-1 sums.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] This ensures that a method to find collisions in one of the hash functions does not defeat data protected by both hash functions.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] For Merkle–Damgård construction hash functions, the concatenated function is as collision-resistant as its strongest component, but not more collision-resistant.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Antoine Joux observed that 2-collisions lead to *n*-collisions: if it is feasible for an attacker to find two messages with the same MD5 hash, then they can find as many additional messages with that same MD5 hash as they desire, with no greater difficulty.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Among those *n* messages with the same MD5 hash, there is likely to be a collision in SHA-1.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The additional work needed to find the SHA-1 collision (beyond the exponential birthday search) requires only polynomial time.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] There are many cryptographic hash algorithms; this section lists a few algorithms that are referenced relatively often.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] A more extensive list can be found on the page containing a comparison of cryptographic hash functions.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 was designed by Ronald Rivest in 1991 to replace an earlier hash function, MD4, and was specified in 1992 as RFC 1321.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against MD5 can be calculated within seconds, which makes the algorithm unsuitable for most use cases where a cryptographic hash is required.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 produces a digest of 128 bits (16 bytes).
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The original specification – now commonly called SHA-0 – of the algorithm was published in 1993 under the title Secure Hash Standard, FIPS PUB 180, by U.S. government standards agency NIST (National Institute of Standards and Technology).
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] It was withdrawn by the NSA shortly after publication and was superseded by the revised version, published in 1995 in FIPS PUB 180-1 and commonly designated SHA-1.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against the full SHA-1 algorithm can be produced using the shattered attack and the hash function should be considered broken.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-1 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Documents may refer to SHA-1 as just "SHA", even though this may conflict with the other Secure Hash Algorithms such as SHA-0, SHA-2, and SHA-3.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD (RACE Integrity Primitives Evaluation Message Digest) is a family of cryptographic hash functions developed in Leuven, Belgium, by Hans Dobbertin, Antoon Bosselaers, and Bart Preneel at the COSIC research group at the Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, and first published in 1996.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD was based upon the design principles used in MD4 and is similar in performance to the more popular SHA-1.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD-160 has, however, not been broken.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] As the name implies, RIPEMD-160 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is a cryptographic hash function designed by Vincent Rijmen and Paulo S.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Barreto, who first described it in 2000.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is based on a substantially modified version of the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES).
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool produces a hash digest of 512 bits (64 bytes).
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 (Secure Hash Algorithm 2) is a set of cryptographic hash functions designed by the United States National Security Agency (NSA), first published in 2001.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] They are built using the Merkle–Damgård structure, from a one-way compression function itself built using the Davies–Meyer structure from a (classified) specialized block cipher.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 basically consists of two hash algorithms: SHA-256 and SHA-512.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-224 is a variant of SHA-256 with different starting values and truncated output.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-512 is more secure than SHA-256 and is commonly faster than SHA-256 on 64-bit machines such as AMD64.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The output size in bits is given by the extension to the "SHA" name, so SHA-224 has an output size of 224 bits (28 bytes); SHA-256, 32 bytes; SHA-384, 48 bytes; and SHA-512, 64 bytes.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 (Secure Hash Algorithm 3) was released by NIST on August 5, 2015.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 is a subset of the broader cryptographic primitive family Keccak.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The Keccak algorithm is the work of Guido Bertoni, Joan Daemen, Michael Peeters, and Gilles Van Assche.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Keccak is based on a sponge construction, which can also be used to build other cryptographic primitives such as a stream cipher.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 provides the same output sizes as SHA-2: 224, 256, 384, and 512 bits.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Configurable output sizes can also be obtained using the SHAKE-128 and SHAKE-256 functions.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Here the -128 and -256 extensions to the name imply the security strength of the function rather than the output size in bits.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE2, an improved version of BLAKE, was announced on December 21, 2012.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn, and Christian Winnerlein with the goal of replacing the widely used but broken MD5 and SHA-1 algorithms.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] When run on 64-bit x64 and ARM architectures, BLAKE2b is faster than SHA-3, SHA-2, SHA-1, and MD5.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Although BLAKE and BLAKE2 have not been standardized as SHA-3 has, BLAKE2 has been used in many protocols including the Argon2 password hash, for the high efficiency that it offers on modern CPUs.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] As BLAKE was a candidate for SHA-3, BLAKE and BLAKE2 both offer the same output sizes as SHA-3 – including a configurable output size.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3, an improved version of BLAKE2, was announced on January 9, 2020.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jack O'Connor, Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, and Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3 is a single algorithm, in contrast to BLAKE and BLAKE2, which are algorithm families with multiple variants.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The BLAKE3 compression function is closely based on that of BLAKE2s, with the biggest difference being that the number of rounds is reduced from 10 to 7.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Internally, BLAKE3 is a Merkle tree, and it supports higher degrees of parallelism than BLAKE2.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] There is a long list of cryptographic hash functions but many have been found to be vulnerable and should not be used.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Even if a hash function has never been broken, a successful attack against a weakened variant may undermine the experts' confidence.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in August 2004 collisions were found in several then-popular hash functions, including MD5.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] These weaknesses called into question the security of stronger algorithms derived from the weak hash functions – in particular, SHA-1 (a strengthened version of SHA-0), RIPEMD-128, and RIPEMD-160 (both strengthened versions of RIPEMD).
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] On August 12, 2004, Joux, Carribault, Lemuel, and Jalby announced a collision for the full SHA-0 algorithm.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Joux et al. accomplished this using a generalization of the Chabaud and Joux attack.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] They found that the collision had complexity 251 and took about 80,000 CPU hours on a supercomputer with 256 Itanium 2 processors – equivalent to 13 days of full-time use of the supercomputer.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] In February 2005, an attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collision in about 269 hashing operations, rather than the 280 expected for a 160-bit hash function.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] In August 2005, another attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collisions in 263 operations.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Other theoretical weaknesses of SHA-1 have been known, and in February 2017 Google announced a collision in SHA-1.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Security researchers recommend that new applications can avoid these problems by using later members of the SHA family, such as SHA-2, or using techniques such as randomized hashing that do not require collision resistance.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] A successful, practical attack broke MD5 (used within certificates for Transport Layer Security) in 2008.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Many cryptographic hashes are based on the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] All cryptographic hashes that directly use the full output of a Merkle–Damgård construction are vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] This makes the MD5, SHA-1, RIPEMD-160, Whirlpool, and the SHA-256 / SHA-512 hash algorithms all vulnerable to this specific attack.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3, BLAKE2, BLAKE3, and the truncated SHA-2 variants are not vulnerable to this type of attack.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Rather than store plain user passwords, controlled-access systems frequently store the hash of each user's password in a file or database.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] When someone requests access, the password they submit is hashed and compared with the stored value.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] If the database is stolen (an all-too-frequent occurrence), the thief will only have the hash values, not the passwords.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Passwords may still be retrieved by an attacker from the hashes, because most people choose passwords in predictable ways.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Lists of common passwords are widely circulated and many passwords are short enough that even all possible combinations may be tested if calculation of the hash does not take too much time.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The use of cryptographic salt prevents some attacks, such as building files of precomputing hash values, e.g. rainbow tables.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] But searches on the order of 100 billion tests per second are possible with high-end graphics processors, making direct attacks possible even with salt.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] The United States National Institute of Standards and Technology recommends storing passwords using special hashes called key derivation functions (KDFs) that have been created to slow brute force searches.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] Slow hashes include pbkdf2, bcrypt, scrypt, argon2, Balloon and some recent modes of Unix crypt.
[src:zk-snarks/cryptographic-hash-function] For KDFs that perform multiple hashes to slow execution, NIST recommends an iteration count of 10,000 or more.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The protocol is open source and based on CryptoNote v2, a concept described in a 2013 white paper authored by Nicolas van Saberhagen.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Developers used this concept to design Monero, and deployed its mainnet in 2014.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The Monero protocol includes various methods to obfuscate transaction details, though users can optionally share view keys for third-party auditing.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Transactions are validated through a miner network running RandomX, a proof-of-work algorithm.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The algorithm issues new coins to miners and was designed to be resistant against application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) mining.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Monero's privacy features have attracted cypherpunks and users desiring privacy measures not provided in other cryptocurrencies.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] A 2022 study in *FSI Digital Investigations* concluded "For now, Monero is untraceable.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] However, it is probably only a matter of time and effort before it changes." Due to its perceived untraceability Monero is gaining increased use in illicit activities such as money laundering, darknet markets, ransomware, cryptojacking, and other organized crime.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Monero's roots trace back to CryptoNote v2, a cryptocurrency protocol first introduced in a white paper published by the presumed pseudonymous Nicolas van Saberhagen in October 2013.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] In the paper, the author described privacy and anonymity as "the most important aspects of electronic cash" and characterized bitcoin's traceability as a "critical flaw".
[src:zk-snarks/monero] A Bitcointalk forum user known as "*thankful_for_today*" implemented these ideas into a coin they called BitMonero.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] However, other forum users disagreed with *thankful_for_today'*s direction for BitMonero and decided to fork it in 2014, leading to the creation of Monero.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] *Monero* translates to *coin* in Esperanto.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The plural of monero ("moneroj") is likewise formed using Esperanto grammar.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Both van Saberhagen and *thankful_for_today* remain anonymous.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Monero has the third-largest community of developers, behind bitcoin and Ethereum.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The protocol's lead maintainer was previously South African developer Riccardo Spagni.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Much of the core development team chooses to remain anonymous.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Monero's key features are those around privacy and anonymity.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Even though it is a public and decentralized ledger, all transaction details are obfuscated.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] This contrasts to bitcoin, where all transaction details, user addresses, and wallet balances are public and transparent.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] These features have given Monero a loyal following among crypto anarchists, cypherpunks, and privacy advocates.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The transaction outputs, or notes, of users sending Monero are obfuscated through ring signatures, which groups a sender's outputs with other decoy outputs.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Encryption of transaction amounts began in 2017 with the implementation of ring confidential transactions (RingCTs).
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Developers also implemented a zero-knowledge proof method, "Bulletproofs", which guarantee a transaction occurred without revealing its value.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Monero recipients are protected through "stealth addresses", public keys generated by the sender that are untraceable to the receiver by a network observer.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] These privacy features are enforced on the network by default.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Monero uses Dandelion++, a protocol which obscures the IP address of devices producing transactions.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] In April 2017, researchers highlighted three major threats to Monero users' privacy.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The first relies on leveraging the ring signature size of zero, and ability to see the output amounts.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The second, "Leveraging Output Merging", involves tracking transactions where two outputs belong to the same user, such as when they send funds to themselves ("churning").
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Finally, "Temporal Analysis", shows that predicting the right output in a ring signature could potentially be easier than previously thought.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] In 2018, researchers presented possible vulnerabilities in a paper titled "An Empirical Analysis of Traceability in the Monero Blockchain".
[src:zk-snarks/monero] In September 2020, the United States Internal Revenue Service's criminal investigation division (IRS-CI), posted a $625,000 bounty for contractors who could develop tools to help trace Monero, other privacy-enhanced cryptocurrencies, the Bitcoin Lightning Network, or other "layer 2" protocol.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The contract was awarded to blockchain analysis groups Chainalysis and Integra FEC.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] In 2021, researchers presented a transaction-flooding attack against Monero’s transaction-graph privacy at the IEEE International Conference on Blockchain and Cryptocurrency.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Under specific assumptions about transaction structure and fees, the "FloodXMR" attack modelled how an adversary who floods the blockchain with their own transactions could, over time, deanonymize a substantial fraction of new transaction inputs at relatively low cost.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Monero uses a proof-of-work algorithm, RandomX, to validate transactions.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The method was introduced in November 2019 to replace the former algorithm CryptoNightR.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Both algorithms were designed to be resistant to ASIC mining, which is commonly used to mine other cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Monero's privacy features have made it popular for illicit purposes.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] On-chain data from 2024 and 2025 shows that Monero’s transaction volumes remained significantly higher than in the 2020–2021 period, stabilizing at an elevated baseline that indicates sustained, regular demand rather than temporary speculation.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] After a wave of cryptocurrency exchange delistings in 2024–2025, Monero trading migrated to decentralized and peer-to-peer platforms, demonstrating resilient usage and ongoing demand.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Monero's privacy features have made it the dominant cryptocurrency on darknet markets (DNMs), where anonymity is critical for both buyers and sellers.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Unlike Bitcoin, whose public ledger enables traceable blockchain analysis, Monero obscures sender, receiver, and transaction amounts by default.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] In August 2016, dark market AlphaBay permitted its vendors to start accepting Monero as an alternative to bitcoin.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The site was taken offline by law enforcement in 2017, but it was relaunched in 2021 with Monero as the sole permitted currency.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] A 2024 report covered by *Wired* found that vendors of child sexual abuse material increasingly used Monero for laundering proceeds through instant exchangers, with blockchain analysis firm Chainalysis describing Monero as "the currency of choice" for this purpose.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] By 2025, nearly half of newly launched darknet markets operated exclusively with Monero, a sharp increase from earlier years, driven by law enforcement advances in tracing Bitcoin and stablecoins.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] This trend has created a perception that markets relying solely on Bitcoin are less secure, pushing users toward Monero-only platforms that better protect against financial surveillance.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] A prominent example was White House Market, a darknet marketplace active from 2019 to 2021 that was used to traffic fentanyl and cocaine; the platform handled transactions in Monero and was referenced in multiple federal indictments.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The market's closure did not halt the broader shift, as subsequent DNMs increasingly adopted Monero-only models that users deem more trustworthy because of the difficulty of tracing XMR payments.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The United States Department of Justice and the Treasury Department have identified Monero as a frequently used tool in darknet and ransomware-related money laundering, with sanctioned exchangers processing hundreds of millions of dollars in XMR.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] In late 2017, malware and antivirus service providers blocked Coinhive, a JavaScript implementation of a Monero miner that was embedded in websites and apps, in some cases by hackers.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Coinhive wrote the script as an alternative to advertisements; a website or app could embed it, and use website visitors' CPU to mine the cryptocurrency while the visitor is consuming the content of the webpage, with the site or app owner getting a percentage of the mined coins.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Some websites and apps did this without informing visitors, or in some cases using all possible system resources.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] As a result, the script was blocked by companies offering ad blocking subscription lists, antivirus services, and antimalware services.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Coinhive had been previously found hidden in *Showtime-*owned streaming platforms and Starbucks Wi-Fi hotspots in Argentina.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Researchers in 2018 found similar malware that mined Monero and sent it to Kim Il-sung University in North Korea.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Monero is sometimes used by ransomware groups.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] According to CNBC, in the first half of 2018, Monero was used in 44% of cryptocurrency ransomware attacks.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The perpetrators of the 2017 WannaCry ransomware attack, which was attributed by the US government to North Korean threat actors, attempted to exchange the ransom they collected in Bitcoin to Monero.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] *Ars Technica* and *Fast Company* reported that the exchange was successful, but BBC News reported that the service the criminals attempted to use, ShapeShift, denied any such transfer.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The Shadow Brokers, who leaked the exploits which were subsequently used in WannaCry but are unlikely to have been involved in the attack, began accepting Monero as payment later in 2017.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] In 2021, CNBC, the *Financial Times*, and *Newsweek* reported that demand for Monero was increasing following the recovery of a bitcoin ransom paid in the Colonial Pipeline cyber attack.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The May 2021 hack forced the pipeline to pay a $4.4M ransom in bitcoin, though a large portion was recovered by the United States federal government the following month.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The group behind the attack, DarkSide, normally requests payment in either bitcoin or Monero, but charge a 10–20% premium for payments made in bitcoin due to its increased traceability risk.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Ransomware group REvil removed the option of paying ransom in bitcoin in 2021, demanding only Monero.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Ransomware negotiators, groups that help victims pay ransoms, have contacted Monero developers to understand the technology.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Despite this, CNBC reported that bitcoin was still the currency of choice demanded in most ransomware attacks, as insurers refuse to pay Monero ransom payments because of traceability concerns.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The attribution of Monero to illicit markets has influenced some exchanges to forgo listing it.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] This has made it more difficult for users to exchange Monero for fiat currencies or other cryptocurrencies.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] Exchanges in South Korea and Australia have delisted Monero and other privacy coins due to regulatory pressure.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] In 2018, Europol and its director Rob Wainwright wrote that the year would see criminals shift from using bitcoin to using Monero, as well as Ethereum, Dash, and Zcash.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] *Bloomberg* and CNN reported that this demand for Monero was because authorities were becoming better at monitoring the Bitcoin blockchain.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] On 20 February 2024, the cryptocurrency exchange Binance delisted Monero, citing regulatory compliance.
[src:zk-snarks/monero] The United States Internal Revenue Service (IRS) has offered funding for contractors that can develop Monero tracing technologies.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] The key advantage of non-interactive zero-knowledge proofs is that they can be used in situations where there is no possibility of interaction between the prover and verifier, such as in online transactions where the two parties are not able to communicate in real time.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] This makes non-interactive zero-knowledge proofs particularly useful in decentralized systems like blockchains, where transactions are verified by a network of nodes and there is no central authority to oversee the verification process.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Most non-interactive zero-knowledge proofs are based on mathematical constructs like elliptic curve cryptography or pairing-based cryptography, which allow for the creation of short and easily verifiable proofs of the truth of a statement.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Unlike interactive zero-knowledge proofs, which require multiple rounds of interaction between the prover and verifier, non-interactive zero-knowledge proofs are designed to be efficient and can be used to verify a large number of statements simultaneously.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Blum, Feldman, and Micali showed in 1988 that a common reference string shared between the prover and the verifier is sufficient to achieve computational zero-knowledge without requiring interaction.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Goldreich and Oren gave impossibility results for one shot zero-knowledge protocols in the standard model.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] In 2003, Shafi Goldwasser and Yael Tauman Kalai published an instance of an identification scheme for which any hash function will yield an insecure digital signature scheme.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] The model influences the properties that can be obtained from a zero-knowledge protocol.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Pass showed that in the common reference string model non-interactive zero-knowledge protocols do not preserve all of the properties of interactive zero-knowledge protocols; e.g., they do not preserve deniability.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Non-interactive zero-knowledge proofs can also be obtained in the random oracle model using the Fiat–Shamir heuristic.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] In 2012, Alessandro Chiesa et al developed the zk-SNARK protocol, an acronym for *zero-knowledge succinct non-interactive argument of knowledge*.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] The first widespread application of zk-SNARKs was in the Zerocash blockchain protocol, where zero-knowledge cryptography provides the computational backbone, by facilitating mathematical proofs that one party has possession of certain information without revealing what that information is.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Zcash utilized zk-SNARKs to facilitate four distinct transaction types: private, shielding, deshielding, and public.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] This protocol allowed users to determine how much data was shared with the public ledger for each transaction.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Ethereum zk-Rollups also utilize zk-SNARKs to increase scalability.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] In 2017, *Bulletproofs* was released, which enable proving that a committed value is in a range using a logarithmic (in the bit length of the range) number of field and group elements.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Bulletproofs was later implemented into Mimblewimble protocol (the basis for Grin and Beam, and Litecoin via extension blocks) and Monero cryptocurrency.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] In 2018, the *zk-STARK* (zero-knowledge Scalable Transparent Argument of Knowledge) protocol was introduced by Eli Ben-Sasson, Iddo Bentov, Yinon Horesh, and Michael Riabzev, offering transparency (no trusted setup), quasi-linear proving time, and poly-logarithmic verification time.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Unlike the first generation of zk-SNARKs, zk-STARKs, by default, do not require a trusted setup, which makes them particularly useful for decentralized applications like blockchains.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Additionally, zk-STARKs can be used to verify many statements at once, making them scalable and efficient.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] In 2019, HALO recursive zk-SNARKs without a trusted setup were presented.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Pickles zk-SNARKs, based on the former construction, power Mina, the first succinctly verifiable blockchain.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] A list of zero-knowledge proof protocols and libraries is provided below along with comparisons based on transparency, universality, and plausible post-quantum security.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] A transparent protocol is one that does not require any trusted setup and uses public randomness.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] A universal protocol is one that does not require a separate trusted setup for each circuit.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Finally, a plausibly post-quantum protocol is one that is not susceptible to known attacks involving quantum algorithms.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Originally, non-interactive zero-knowledge was only defined as a single theorem-proof system.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] In such a system each proof requires its own fresh common reference string.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] A common reference string in general is not a random string.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] It may, for instance, consist of randomly chosen group elements that all protocol parties use.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Although the group elements are random, the reference string is not as it contains a certain structure (e.g., group elements) that is distinguishable from randomness.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Subsequently, Feige, Lapidot, and Shamir introduced multi-theorem zero-knowledge proofs as a more versatile notion for non-interactive zero-knowledge proofs.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Pairing-based cryptography has led to several cryptographic advancements.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] One of these advancements is more powerful and more efficient non-interactive zero-knowledge proofs.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] The seminal idea was to hide the values for the pairing evaluation in a commitment.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Using different commitment schemes, this idea was used to build zero-knowledge proof systems under the sub-group hiding and under the decisional linear assumption.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] These proof systems prove circuit satisfiability, and thus by the Cook–Levin theorem allow proving membership for every language in NP.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] The size of the common reference string and the proofs is relatively small; however, transforming a statement into a boolean circuit incurs considerable overhead.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Proof systems under the sub-group hiding, decisional linear assumption, and external Diffie–Hellman assumption that allow directly proving the pairing product equations that are common in pairing-based cryptography have been proposed.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] Under strong knowledge assumptions, it is known how to create sublinear-length computationally-sound proof systems for NP-complete languages.
[src:zk-snarks/non-interactive-zero-knowledge-proof] More precisely, the proof in such proof systems consists only of a small number of bilinear group elements.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:zk-snarks/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] Launched in October 2016, Zcash was developed by cryptographers at Johns Hopkins University and MIT and derived its code from bitcoin.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] Zcash was one of the first large-scale implementations of zero-knowledge proofs outside of academia.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] Zcash is modeled on bitcoin, sharing its proof-of-work consensus mechanism.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] In 2016, Tom Robinson, co-founder of blockchain tracing firm Elliptic, told CNBC that Zcash appeared to have achieved a high level of anonymity.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] Zcash supports two types of addresses: transparent addresses, which function similarly to bitcoin addresses with publicly visible transactions, and shielded addresses, which use zero-knowledge proofs to encrypt transaction data.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] Shielded transactions can be verified as valid without revealing the sender, recipient, or amount transferred.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] Users can transact between the two types, allowing funds to move between the transparent and shielded pools.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] This optional privacy model is intended to preserve fungibility, allowing units of the currency to be treated equally regardless of their transaction history.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] Users also have the option to share private viewing keys, allowing designated third parties to see their transaction details for auditing purposes.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] A 2018 study found that while it is possible to use Zcash privately, the anonymity set of the shielded pool could be reduced through heuristics-based analysis of usage patterns.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] The analysis predates subsequent protocol upgrades to the shielded transaction system.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] In 2022, journalist Andy Greenberg described Zcash's shielded transactions as "provably inaccessible" to surveillance and said he had not seen evidence that its anonymity could be compromised.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] Development work on Zcash began in 2013 by Johns Hopkins University professor Matthew Green and his graduate students Ian Miers and Christina Garman, who developed the Zerocoin protocol.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] They subsequently joined forces with a team of cryptographers including Alessandro Chiesa and Madars Virza from MIT, and Eli Ben-Sasson from the Technion and Eran Tromer from Tel Aviv University, who had developed a more efficient variant called zk-SNARKs.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] The development was completed by the for-profit Zcash Company, led by Zooko Wilcox, a Colorado based computer security specialist.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] The Zcash Company raised over $3 million from investors including Naval Ravikant.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] Zcash was first mined in late October 2016.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] To generate revenue, 10% of all coins mined for the first four years were automatically distributed to the Zcash Company and the Zcash Foundation.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] The instantiation of the Zcash network required the creation of a master private key.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] To ensure privacy, this private key must later be destroyed, otherwise counterfeit Zcash coins could be generated.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] To maximize the chance that no one person could obtain the private key, software was written which allowed individuals from six different locations to collaboratively generate the private key, use it to instantiate Zcash, and then destroy the computers used in the process afterwards.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] In 2019, Electric Coin Company researcher Sean Bowe discovered Halo, a technique for generating zero-knowledge proofs without requiring a trusted setup ceremony.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] This eliminated the need for the elaborate multi-party ceremonies used at launch.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] In 2018, *MIT Technology Review* named Zcash co-founder Alessandro Chiesa, an assistant professor at the University of California, Berkeley, to its Innovators Under 35 list for his work on the zero-knowledge proof technology underlying the cryptocurrency.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] In 2022, Edward Snowden revealed that he had participated in the creation of Zcash under the pseudonym "John Dobbertin." Other participants in the ceremony included Peter Todd, a Bitcoin Core developer.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] On February 21, 2019, the "Zcash Company" announced a rebranding as the Electric Coin Company (ECC).
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] In 2020, the Electric Coin Company transitioned to nonprofit ownership, becoming a wholly owned subsidiary of the Bootstrap Project, a 501(c)(3) organization.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] In September 2023, a mining pool named ViaBTC had seized control of over half the hashing power on Zcash.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] This 51% dominance raised worries about a 51% attack, where they could potentially manipulate transactions and harm the network.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] In response, Coinbase placed Zcash markets into "limit-only" mode in an effort to prevent significant price swings.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] In November 2025, Cameron Winklevoss and Tyler Winklevoss invested $50 million to launch Cypherpunk Technologies, a digital-asset treasury company focused on the cryptocurrency.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] Securities and Exchange Commission closed a probe into Zcash.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] In April 2026, Foundry, one of the largest bitcoin mining pool operators, launched a dedicated Zcash mining pool.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] In 2017, JPMorgan Chase integrated Zcash's zero-knowledge proof technology into its enterprise blockchain platform Quorum to enable confidential transactions for business clients.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] *Fortune* reported that Zcash's fundamental technology would be added to the Ethereum network.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] In late 2017, Grayscale Investments launched a Zcash investment fund, which is the company's third dedicated cryptocurrency fund after bitcoin and Ethereum Classic.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] In 2026, Grayscale filed with regulators to convert the fund into an exchange-traded fund.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] In May 2018, the New York State Department of Financial Services approved Zcash for trading on Gemini.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] The Freedom of the Press Foundation, the Human Rights Foundation, and the Electronic Frontier Foundation have accepted Zcash donations.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] In 2017, the European Union's law enforcement agency Europol flagged Zcash, along with bitcoin and Monero, for potential use in internet-based crime.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] The same report noted that Zcash was not known to have a significant criminal following.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] In 2018, several Japanese exchanges delisted Zcash and other privacy-focused cryptocurrencies citing regulatory pressure following a major exchange hack; the delisted coins had not been involved in the hack.
[src:zk-snarks/zcash] A 2023 analysis of cryptocurrency and crime similarly found that Zcash "featured very rarely on the dark web" compared to Monero.
